A biomolecule composed of chains of amino acid residues.

This article discusses a class of molecules. For the dietary component, see [Protein (nutrient)](/Protein_(nutrient)). For other meanings, consult [Protein (disambiguation)](/Protein_(disambiguation)).

The image displays a three-dimensional representation of the protein [myoglobin](/Myoglobin), prominently featuring turquoise [α-helices](/Alpha_helix). This particular protein holds historical significance as the first whose structure was elucidated through [X-ray crystallography](/X-ray_crystallography). Towards the central-right portion of the coiled structure, a [prosthetic group](/Prosthetic_group) known as a [heme group](/Heme_group) is visible, with an oxygen molecule (rendered in red) attached.

Proteins are substantial [biomolecules](/Biomolecule) and [macromolecules](/Macromolecule), each constructed from one or more extended chains of [amino acid](/Amino_acid) [residues](/Residue_(biochemistry)). They are responsible for an astonishingly diverse range of functions within living organisms. These functions include the [catalysis of metabolic reactions](/Enzyme_catalysis), the intricate process of [DNA replication](/DNA_replication), [responding to external and internal stimuli](/Cell_signaling), providing essential [structural support to cells](/Cytoskeleton) and entire [organisms](/Fibrous_protein), and facilitating the [transport of molecules](/Intracellular_transport) across cellular boundaries and throughout the body. The unique characteristics of each protein are primarily determined by its specific sequence of amino acids, a sequence dictated by the [nucleotide sequence](/Nucleic_acid_sequence) of its corresponding [gene](/Gene). This sequence, in turn, typically governs the protein's [protein folding](/Protein_folding) into a precise [3D structure](/Protein_structure), which is the ultimate determinant of its biological activity.

A linear sequence of amino acid residues is referred to as a [polypeptide](/Polypeptide). A protein, by definition, contains at least one such long polypeptide chain. Shorter chains, typically comprising fewer than 20–30 residues, are generally not classified as proteins and are commonly designated as [peptides](/Peptide). The amino acid residues within a polypeptide are linked together by [peptide bonds](/Peptide_bond), forming an extended chain. The [sequence](/Protein_primary_structure) of these amino acid residues within a protein is directly encoded by the [sequence](/DNA_sequencing) of the gene responsible for its production, which is itself inscribed within the [genetic code](/Genetic_code). While the standard genetic code specifies 20 common amino acids, certain organisms have evolved to incorporate others, such as [selenocysteine](/Selenocysteine) and, in some [archaea](/Archaea), [pyrrolysine](/Pyrrolysine). Furthermore, shortly after or even during their synthesis, protein residues frequently undergo chemical modifications through a process known as [post-translational modification](/Post-translational_modification). These modifications can significantly alter the protein's physical and chemical properties, its folding stability, its activity, and ultimately, its function. Some proteins also possess non-peptide components, referred to as [prosthetic groups](/Prosthetic_group) or [cofactors](/Cofactor_(biochemistry)). Proteins often collaborate, associating to form stable [protein complexes](/Protein_complex) to carry out more elaborate functions.

Once synthesized, proteins have a finite lifespan within the cell. They are eventually [degraded](/Proteolysis) and their constituent components recycled by the cell's sophisticated machinery through a process called [protein turnover](/Protein_turnover). The lifespan of a protein, often quantified by its [half-life](/Half-life), can vary dramatically, ranging from mere minutes to several years. In mammalian cells, the average lifespan is typically around one to two days. Proteins that are abnormal or misfolded are generally degraded more rapidly, either because they are specifically targeted for destruction or due to inherent instability.

Similar to other fundamental biological macromolecules such as [polysaccharides](/Polysaccharide) and [nucleic acids](/Nucleic_acid), proteins are indispensable components of all living organisms, participating in virtually every biological process occurring within [cells](/Cell_(biology)). A significant proportion of proteins function as [enzymes](/Enzyme), acting as biological catalysts to accelerate biochemical reactions and playing a vital role in [metabolism](/Metabolism). Other proteins are primarily structural, providing mechanical support; examples include [actin](/Actin) and [myosin](/Myosin) in muscle tissue, and the scaffolding proteins that maintain the shape of the [cytoskeleton](/Cytoskeleton). Proteins are also crucial for intercellular communication through [cell signaling](/Cell_signaling), orchestrating [immune responses](/Antibody), facilitating [cell adhesion](/Cell_adhesion), and regulating the [cell cycle](/Cell_cycle). For animals, dietary intake of proteins is essential to supply the [essential amino acids](/Essential_amino_acid) that cannot be [synthesized](/Amino_acid_synthesis) internally. The process of [digestion](/Digestion) breaks down these dietary proteins into their constituent amino acids for metabolic utilization.

## History and etymology

### Discovery and early studies

The scientific exploration of proteins dates back to the 18th century, with pioneers like [Antoine Fourcroy](/Antoine_Fran%C3%A7ois,_comte_de_Fourcroy) and others. These early researchers often grouped these substances under the general term "[albumins](/Albumin)" or "albuminous materials," a concept also recognized in German as *Eiweisskörper*. For instance, [gluten](/Gluten), a protein complex found in wheat, was first isolated and described in published research around 1747, with later studies confirming its presence in numerous plant species. By 1789, Antoine Fourcroy had identified three distinct categories of animal proteins: [albumin](/Albumin), [fibrin](/Fibrin), and [gelatin](/Gelatin). During the late 1700s and early 1800s, plant proteins under investigation included [gluten](/Gluten), [plant albumin](/Albumin), [gliadin](/Gliadin), and [legumin](/Legumin).

The formal description of proteins as a distinct class of molecules is attributed to the Dutch chemist [Gerardus Johannes Mulder](/Gerardus_Johannes_Mulder), with the name "protein" itself being coined by the Swedish chemist [Jöns Jacob Berzelius](/J%C3%B6ns_Jacob_Berzelius) in 1838. Mulder's meticulous [elemental analysis](/Elemental_analysis) of common proteins revealed a striking similarity in their [empirical formula](/Empirical_formula), consistently yielding approximately C 400 H 620 N 100 O 120 P 1 S 1 . This led him to an initially incorrect conclusion that all proteins might be composed of a single, albeit very large, molecular type. Berzelius proposed the term "protein," derived from the ancient [Greek](/Greek_language) word *prōteios* (πρώτειος), signifying "primary," "in the lead," or "standing in front." Mulder's subsequent work also led to the identification of protein degradation products, such as the [amino acid](/Amino_acid) [leucine](/Leucine), for which he determined a molecular weight remarkably close to its actual value of 131&#160;[Da](/Dalton_(unit)).

Early nutritional scientists, such as the German physiologist [Carl von Voit](/Carl_von_Voit), held the view that protein was the most crucial nutrient for maintaining bodily structure, largely based on the prevailing belief that "flesh makes flesh." Around 1862, [Karl Heinrich Ritthausen](/Karl_Heinrich_Ritthausen) succeeded in isolating the amino acid [glutamic acid](/Glutamic_acid). Later, [Thomas Burr Osborne](/Thomas_Burr_Osborne_(chemist)), working at the [Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station](/Connecticut_Agricultural_Experiment_Station), compiled extensive reviews on vegetable proteins. In collaboration with [Lafayette Mendel](/Lafayette_Mendel), Osborne conducted feeding experiments with laboratory rats that led to the identification of several [nutritionally essential amino acids](/Essential_amino_acid). Their findings demonstrated that diets deficient in these essential amino acids resulted in stunted growth in the rats, consistent with [Liebig's law of the minimum](/Liebig%27s_law_of_the_minimum). The final essential amino acid to be discovered was [threonine](/Threonine), identified by [William Cumming Rose](/William_Cumming_Rose).

The progress of early protein biochemistry was significantly hampered by the inherent difficulty in purifying proteins. While large quantities of protein could be obtained from sources like blood, egg whites, and [keratin](/Keratin), isolating individual protein species in a pure form proved challenging. A notable exception occurred in the 1950s when the [Armour Hot Dog Company](/Armour_and_Company) purified a kilogram of bovine pancreatic [ribonuclease A](/Ribonuclease_A) and made it freely available to the scientific community. This generous gesture propelled ribonuclease A to become a central focus of biochemical research for decades.

### Polypeptides

The understanding that proteins are fundamentally [polypeptides](/Polypeptide)—chains of amino acids linked together—crystallized through the pioneering work of [Franz Hofmeister](/Franz_Hofmeister) and [Hermann Emil Fischer](/Hermann_Emil_Fischer) in 1902. However, the central role of proteins as [enzymes](/Enzyme) catalyzing biological reactions wasn't fully appreciated until 1926, when [James B. Sumner](/James_B._Sumner) definitively demonstrated that the enzyme [urease](/Urease) was, in fact, a protein.

[Linus Pauling](/Linus_Pauling) is credited with the groundbreaking prediction of regular protein [secondary structures](/Secondary_structure), based on the principle of [hydrogen bonding](/Hydrogen_bonding), a concept initially proposed by [William Astbury](/William_Astbury) in 1933. Subsequent research by [Walter Kauzmann](/Walter_Kauzmann) on [denaturation](/Denaturation_(biochemistry)), building upon earlier studies by [Kaj Linderstrøm-Lang](/Kaj_Ulrik_Linderstr%C3%B8m-Lang), provided crucial insights into the mechanisms of [protein folding](/Protein_folding) and structure, particularly highlighting the role of [hydrophobic interactions](/Hydrophobic_core).

The first complete amino acid [sequencing](/Protein_sequencing) of a protein was achieved for [insulin](/Insulin) by [Frederick Sanger](/Frederick_Sanger) in 1949. Sanger's precise determination of the insulin amino acid sequence provided conclusive evidence that proteins are linear polymers of amino acids, definitively refuting earlier hypotheses of branched chains, [colloids](/Colloid), or [cyclols](/Cyclol). His remarkable achievement earned him the Nobel Prize in 1958. Later, [Christian Anfinsen](/Christian_Anfinsen)'s studies on the [oxidative folding](/Oxidative_folding) process of ribonuclease A, for which he was awarded the Nobel Prize in 1972, firmly established the [thermodynamic hypothesis](/Thermodynamic_hypothesis) of protein folding, postulating that the native, folded state of a protein represents its minimum [free energy](/Free_energy_(thermodynamics)) conformation.

## Structure

[John Kendrew](/John_Kendrew) is shown here with a model of myoglobin under construction.

The advent of [X-ray crystallography](/X-ray_crystallography) revolutionized the field, enabling not only the determination of protein sequences but also their intricate three-dimensional structures. &#91;25&#93; The first protein structures to be elucidated were those of [hemoglobin](/Hemoglobin) by [Max Perutz](/Max_Perutz) and [myoglobin](/Myoglobin) by [John Kendrew](/John_Kendrew), both reported in 1958. &#91;26&#93; &#91;27&#93; The increasing power of computational resources has been instrumental in advancing the sequencing of increasingly complex proteins. For instance, in 1999, [Roger Kornberg](/Roger_Kornberg) determined the highly complex structure of [RNA polymerase](/RNA_polymerase) using high-intensity X-rays sourced from [synchrotrons](/Synchrotrons). &#91;25&#93;

More recently, [cryo-electron microscopy](/Cryo-electron_microscopy) (cryo-EM) has emerged as a powerful technique for visualizing large [macromolecular assemblies](/Macromolecular_Assembly). &#91;28&#93; Unlike X-ray crystallography, cryo-EM involves freezing protein samples and utilizing [electron beams](/Electron_microscopy) rather than X-rays. This method is less damaging to the sample, allowing scientists to gather more detailed information and analyze larger structures. &#91;25&#93; Concurrently, computational [protein structure prediction](/Protein_structure_prediction) methods, particularly for smaller protein [structural domains](/Structural_domain), &#91;29&#93; have made significant strides, bringing researchers closer to achieving atomic-level resolution of protein structures.

As of April 2024, the [Protein Data Bank](/Protein_Data_Bank) houses an extensive collection of over 181,018 structures determined by X-ray crystallography, 19,809 by cryo-EM, and 12,697 by [NMR](/Protein_nuclear_magnetic_resonance_spectroscopy) spectroscopy. &#91;30&#93;

## Classification

### Protein families, Gene Ontology, and EC numbers

Proteins are primarily classified based on their amino acid sequence and three-dimensional structure. However, other classification systems are also widely employed. For enzymes, the [Enzyme Commission number](/Enzyme_Commission_number) (EC number) system provides a standardized functional classification. Similarly, the [Gene Ontology](/Gene_Ontology) (GO) project offers a framework for classifying genes and proteins based on their biological roles, biochemical functions, and subcellular localization.

Sequence similarity serves as a crucial criterion for classifying proteins, reflecting both evolutionary relationships and functional similarities. This analysis can be performed on entire proteins or, more commonly, on individual [protein domains](/Protein_domain), especially in the context of [multi-domain proteins](/Protein_domain). Protein domains are particularly useful for classification as they represent distinct structural and functional units that can be combined in various ways. A study encompassing approximately 170,000 proteins revealed that about two-thirds could be assigned at least one domain, with larger proteins typically possessing a greater number of domains (for example, proteins exceeding 600 [amino acids](/Amino_acid) averaged over five domains). &#91;33&#93;

## Biochemistry

### Chemical structure and the peptide bond

The vast majority of proteins are constructed from linear [polymers](/Polymer) composed of a sequence of up to 20 different L-α-amino acids. With the exception of [proline](/Proline), all [proteinogenic amino acids](/Proteinogenic_amino_acid) share a common structural core: an [α-carbon](/Alpha_carbon) atom covalently bonded to an [amino](/Amino) group, a [carboxyl](/Carboxyl) group, and a variable [side chain](/Side_chain). Proline's unique cyclic side chain, which attaches to its own amino group, restricts the flexibility of the protein chain. &#91;34&#93; The side chains of the [standard amino acids](/List_of_standard_amino_acids) exhibit a wide array of chemical structures and properties, and it is the collective influence of all these amino acids that ultimately dictates the protein's three-dimensional conformation and its chemical reactivity. &#91;35&#93;

Amino acids within a polypeptide chain are joined by [peptide bonds](/Peptide_bond) formed between the amino group of one amino acid and the carboxyl group of another. Each amino acid residue within the chain retains its identity, and the continuous chain of carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen atoms constitutes the main chain, or protein backbone. &#91;36&#93; &#58;&#8202;19&#8202; The peptide bond itself exhibits [resonance](/Resonance_(chemistry)) structures, imparting a degree of [double-bond](/Double-bond) character to the backbone. This characteristic renders the alpha carbons, the nitrogen atom, and the carbonyl group (C=O) roughly [coplanar](/Coplanar). The rotational freedom around the remaining two [dihedral angles](/Dihedral_angle) within the peptide unit dictates the local spatial arrangement of the protein backbone. Consequently, proteins possess a degree of inherent rigidity. &#91;36&#93; &#58;&#8202;31&#8202; A polypeptide chain terminates with a free amino group at one end, known as the [N-terminus](/N-terminus) or amino terminus, and a free carboxyl group at the other, termed the [C-terminus](/C-terminus) or carboxy terminus. &#91;37&#93; By convention, amino acid sequences are written from the N-terminus to the C-terminus, mirroring the directionality of protein [synthesis by ribosomes](/Translation_(biology)). &#91;37&#93; &#91;38&#93;

The terms protein, polypeptide, and [peptide](/Peptide) are not always strictly defined and can sometimes overlap in usage. "Protein" generally refers to the complete, biologically active molecule in its stable, folded conformation, while "peptide" is typically reserved for shorter amino acid oligomers that may not possess a stable three-dimensional structure. However, the distinction is often blurred, with the boundary usually lying around 20–30 amino acid residues. &#91;39&#93;

Proteins possess the remarkable ability to interact with a vast array of molecules and ions, including [other proteins](/Protein%E2%80%93protein_interaction), [lipids](/Protein%E2%80%93lipid_interaction), [carbohydrates](/Protein%E2%80%93carbohydrate_interaction), and [DNA](/Protein%E2%80%93DNA_interaction). &#91;40&#93; &#91;41&#93; &#91;42&#93;

### Abundance in cells

A typical [bacterial](/Bacteria) cell, such as [E. coli](/Escherichia_coli) or [Staphylococcus aureus](/Staphylococcus_aureus), is estimated to harbor approximately 2 million protein molecules. Smaller bacteria, like [Mycoplasma](/Mycoplasma) or [spirochetes](/Spirochaete), contain fewer proteins, ranging from about 50,000 to 1 million. In contrast, [eukaryotic](/Eukaryote) cells, being larger and more complex, contain significantly more protein. For example, [yeast](/Saccharomyces_cerevisiae) cells are estimated to contain around 50 million proteins, while [human](/Human) cells contain on the order of 1 to 3 billion. &#91;43&#93; The concentration of individual protein copies within a cell can span from just a few molecules to as many as 20 million. &#91;44&#93; It's important to note that not all genes encoding proteins are expressed in every cell; the number of proteins present depends on factors such as cell type and external stimuli. For instance, of the roughly 20,000 proteins encoded by the human genome, only about 6,000 have been detected in [lymphoblastoid](/Lymphoblastoid) cells. &#91;45&#93; The most abundant protein known in nature is widely considered to be [RuBisCO](/RuBisCO), an enzyme crucial for [photosynthesis](/Photosynthesis) as it catalyzes the incorporation of [carbon dioxide](/Carbon_dioxide) into organic matter. In plants, RuBisCO can constitute as much as 1% of their total dry weight. &#91;46&#93;

## Synthesis

### Biosynthesis

The [DNA](/DNA) sequence of a gene ultimately dictates the amino acid sequence of a protein.

The [DNA](/DNA) sequence of a gene [encodes](/Genetic_code) the amino acid sequence of a protein.

Proteins are assembled from amino acids, with the information for their specific sequence encoded in genes. Each protein possesses a unique amino acid sequence determined by the [nucleotide](/Nucleotide) sequence of the gene responsible for its synthesis. The [genetic code](/Genetic_code) is structured as a series of three-nucleotide units called [codons](/Codon), with each codon specifying a particular amino acid. For example, the codon AUG (composed of [adenine](/Adenine), [uracil](/Uracil), and [guanine](/Guanine)) codes for the amino acid [methionine](/Methionine). Given that DNA utilizes four distinct nucleotides, there are 64 possible codon combinations, leading to redundancy in the genetic code, where some amino acids are specified by multiple codons. &#91;42&#93; &#58;&#8202;1002–42&#8202; In organisms, genes encoded in DNA are first [transcribed](/Transcription_(genetics)) into precursor [messenger RNA](/Messenger_RNA) (mRNA) by enzymes such as [RNA polymerase](/RNA_polymerase). Most organisms then process this pre-mRNA (also known as a primary transcript) through various forms of [post-transcriptional modification](/Post-transcriptional_modification) to yield mature mRNA. This mature mRNA then serves as the template for protein synthesis by the [ribosome](/Ribosome). In [prokaryotes](/Prokaryote), mRNA can be translated as it is being produced or immediately after it detaches from the [nucleoid](/Nucleoid). Conversely, in [eukaryotes](/Eukaryote), mRNA is synthesized within the [cell nucleus](/Cell_nucleus) and subsequently transported across the [nuclear membrane](/Nuclear_membrane) into the [cytoplasm](/Cytoplasm), where [protein synthesis](/Protein_biosynthesis) takes place. The rate of protein synthesis is generally higher in prokaryotes compared to eukaryotes, potentially reaching up to 20 amino acids per second. &#91;47&#93;

The process of synthesizing a protein from an mRNA template is termed [translation](/Translation_(genetics)). The mRNA molecule is loaded onto the ribosome, where it is read in three-nucleotide increments. Each codon on the mRNA is matched by a complementary [base pair](/Base_pair) on an [anticodon](/Anticodon) located on a [transfer RNA](/Transfer_RNA) (tRNA) molecule. Each tRNA molecule carries the specific amino acid corresponding to the codon it recognizes. The enzyme [aminoacyl tRNA synthetase](/Aminoacyl_tRNA_synthetase) is responsible for "charging" the tRNA molecules with the correct amino acids. The growing polypeptide chain is often referred to as the nascent chain. Protein synthesis always proceeds in the direction from the [N-terminus](/N-terminus) to the [C-terminus](/C-terminus). &#91;42&#93; &#58;&#8202;1002–42&#8202;

The size of a synthesized protein is typically described by the number of amino acids it contains and its total [molecular mass](/Molecular_mass), usually expressed in daltons (Da) or kilodaltons (kDa). The average protein size tends to increase from Archaea to Bacteria to Eukaryotes, with corresponding average lengths of 283, 311, and 438 residues, and molecular masses of 31, 34, and 49 kDa, respectively. This increase is attributed to a greater number of [protein domains](/Protein_domain) that often constitute proteins in more complex organisms. &#91;48&#93; For instance, proteins in [yeast](/Yeast) average 466 amino acids in length and have a molecular mass of 53 kDa. &#91;39&#93; The largest known proteins are the [titins](/Titin), a crucial component of the [muscle](/Muscle) [sarcomere](/Sarcomere), which possess a molecular mass of nearly 3000 kDa and extend to approximately 27,000 amino acids in length. &#91;49&#93;

### Chemical synthesis

#### Peptide Synthesis

Short proteins, or peptides, can be synthesized chemically using a variety of [peptide synthesis](/Peptide_synthesis) methods. These techniques leverage [organic synthesis](/Organic_synthesis) principles, such as [chemical ligation](/Chemical_ligation), to efficiently produce peptides. &#91;50&#93; Chemical synthesis offers the advantage of incorporating non-natural amino acids into polypeptide chains, for example, by attaching [fluorescent](/Fluorescent) probes to specific amino acid side chains. &#91;51&#93; While these methods are invaluable in laboratory settings for [biochemistry](/Biochemistry) and [cell biology](/Cell_biology), they are generally less practical for large-scale commercial applications. Chemical synthesis becomes inefficient for polypeptides exceeding approximately 300 amino acids, and the resulting proteins may not readily adopt their correct native [tertiary structure](/Tertiary_structure). Notably, most chemical synthesis methods proceed in the reverse direction of biological synthesis, from the C-terminus to the N-terminus. &#91;52&#93;

## Structure

